<seg id="2281">There are many graphical tools for comparing. so why & kdiff3;? let me briefly explain why I wrote.</seg>
<seg id="2282">The merge was very complicated, because one of the contributors had made many changes and at the same time corrected the indentation at many places. another programmer had changed a lot of text in the same file. the result was a lot of conflicts during merging.</seg>
<seg id="2283">The program used by me showed only the changed lines, but I could not see what had changed within these lines. and there was no clue to the places where perhaps only the indentation had changed. bringing these changes was a small nightmare.</seg>
<seg id="2284">So that was the beginning. the first version of & kdiff3; could represent differences within a line and changes to white characters. later, any number of other useful functions were added.</seg>
